Data <- read.csv('data/IE360_Spring22_HW2_data.csv',colClasses=c('character',rep('numeric',10)))
colnames(Data) <- c("Quarters", "UGS", "RNUV","NLPG","PU","PG","NUGV","NDGV","GNPA","GNPC","GNPT")
Data$Quarters <- as.Date(as.yearqtr(Data$Quarters, format = "%Y_Q%q"))
Training <- Data[c(1:28),]
Forecast <- Data[c(29,30,31,32),]
Training <- data.table(Training)
Forecast <- data.table(Forecast)

3) Visualizations of Data¶

In [6]:
ggplot(Training, aes(x=Quarters,y=UGS, group = 1)) +
geom_point() +
geom_line() +
labs(y ='Gasoline Sale in a Quarter (1000m^3)')+ 
ggtitle('Unleaded Gasoline Sales per Quarter')+
geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x, method = "lm",level=0.9)

We can clearly see that there is a seasonality which is a yearly-seasonality from the pattern of every four-quarter period.

In [7]:
mean_series=roll_mean(Training$UGS,4,align='left')
plot(mean_series,
     type='l',col='red',
     xlab = "time (t)",
     ylab = "Rolling Mean",
     main = "Mean series")

From the plot of mean series, it is obtained that there is a declining trend. Also, it shows us that data is not stationary because the Rolling mean changes with respect to time.

In [8]:
var_series=roll_var(Training$UGS,4,align='left')
plot(var_series,
     type='l',col='red',
     xlab = "time (t)",
     ylab = "Rolling Variance",
     main = "Variance series")

In variance series, we can not obtain strong signs about the data whether it is stationary or not as the mean series.

In [9]:
acf(Training$UGS)

This autocorrelation graph also strengths that yearly-seasonality exists in this data. We can see it from each four-quarter period. For example multiples of 4 are higher than others. In addition, Lag 1 shows us the decreasing trend.
